1
00:00:14,792 --> 00:00:17,370
Younes Basil
Muhammad, from Mosul

2
00:00:17,395 --> 00:00:18,906
I am 24 years old

3
00:00:20,078 --> 00:00:22,109
I am not studying or
working at the moment

4
00:00:24,557 --> 00:00:26,745
Interviewer: Are you married?
Witness: No, I’m not married

5
00:00:28,750 --> 00:00:32,135
Tell me about your first
detention experience

6
00:00:32,160 --> 00:00:34,219
Where were you arrested,
and where did they take you?

7
00:00:34,244 --> 00:00:37,291
How long did you stay in the place where you
were detained, and what happened to you there?

8
00:00:38,776 --> 00:00:40,078
They took me from the house

9
00:00:41,250 --> 00:00:42,708
To the Dawasa Center

10
00:00:42,911 --> 00:00:44,344
I stayed with them there

11
00:00:45,698 --> 00:00:47,026
I stayed with them there

12
00:00:47,495 --> 00:00:51,219
And I was tortured, and so on

13
00:00:52,105 --> 00:00:55,542
Then I was transferred to the
<i>Qaimaqam</i> Prison

14
00:00:56,167 --> 00:00:57,625
I stayed there for a week

15
00:00:59,084 --> 00:01:00,230
Then they transferred
me back here

16
00:01:00,255 --> 00:01:03,276
Two days after I was transferred
there, the place was bombed

17
00:01:03,537 --> 00:01:04,839
A plane bombed it

18
00:01:05,985 --> 00:01:09,526
I came and spent one
month and twenty days here

19
00:01:09,839 --> 00:01:10,490
Interviewer: Alright

20
00:01:11,245 --> 00:01:15,620
When they took you there,
what day was it and at what time?

21
00:01:15,645 --> 00:01:18,537
And what was the date when they
came and took you from the house?

22
00:01:19,058 --> 00:01:21,141
What conversation
took place between you?

23
00:01:21,922 --> 00:01:23,355
They took me before Ramadan

24
00:01:25,178 --> 00:01:27,547
They said, We just
need you for a question

25
00:01:27,886 --> 00:01:30,698
We only want to ask you something,
then we’ll return you home

26
00:01:32,443 --> 00:01:35,542
When we reached the
center, they didn’t let me leave

27
00:01:35,567 --> 00:01:38,433
And they told my father, Go, we’ll
keep your son and we won’t let him out

28
00:01:39,787 --> 00:01:40,985
So I stayed two days

29
00:01:42,131 --> 00:01:44,188
Ramadan was near

30
00:01:44,760 --> 00:01:45,933
Ramadan was approaching

31
00:01:48,433 --> 00:01:50,282
I spent the whole
month of Ramadan here

32
00:01:50,829 --> 00:01:52,990
On <i>Laylat al-Qadr</i>,
they cut off my hand

33
00:01:53,015 --> 00:01:54,735
They took me out of here
and amputated my hand

34
00:02:00,672 --> 00:02:05,256
I was put alone in a
room at the Dawasa Center

35
00:02:07,131 --> 00:02:08,797
From morning until evening

36
00:02:09,813 --> 00:02:15,490
Later they put me in a
car — me and three others

37
00:02:16,506 --> 00:02:17,912
They seated us in the car

38
00:02:18,693 --> 00:02:20,490
They shackled our hands
and blindfolded our eyes

39
00:02:20,542 --> 00:02:23,980
And they covered us so
we couldn’t see the place

40
00:02:24,005 --> 00:02:25,464
And we were
transferred to a house

41
00:02:27,131 --> 00:02:29,683
Interviewer: Was the interrogation
and torture carried out in that house?

42
00:02:29,708 --> 00:02:30,256
Yes

43
00:02:30,281 --> 00:02:32,079
Alright, continue the story

44
00:02:32,547 --> 00:02:34,500
We were transferred
there, to the house

45
00:02:35,855 --> 00:02:38,980
Those others — I didn’t
know what their charge was

46
00:02:39,422 --> 00:02:42,235
And my charge was theft, so they
brought me and put me in the room

47
00:02:42,886 --> 00:02:45,047
And they started
interrogating me

48
00:02:45,072 --> 00:02:48,068
About how I’d entered,
what I took, and what I did

49
00:02:49,959 --> 00:02:54,021
I stayed two to three
days in the house

50
00:02:54,490 --> 00:02:56,261
Then I was transferred
afterwards to <i>Qaimaqam</i>

51
00:02:57,614 --> 00:03:03,213
I stayed for about a week,
maybe eight days, at the <i>Qaimaqam</i>

52
00:03:03,238 --> 00:03:05,532
Or a week, roughly
ten days in total

53
00:03:06,573 --> 00:03:09,803
I left there, and they also
brought me before a judge there

54
00:03:10,688 --> 00:03:13,266
He asked me about my
charge too, and I said–Theft

55
00:03:13,291 --> 00:03:16,573
I heard sounds of
flogging and beating

56
00:03:18,735 --> 00:03:22,537
When I went in to see him
they took me back again

57
00:03:23,032 --> 00:03:26,313
When I entered, he was sitting
behind me and I was sitting like this now

58
00:03:26,808 --> 00:03:28,136
I was also sitting on a chair

59
00:03:28,474 --> 00:03:29,881
And he sat behind
me asking questions

60
00:03:31,292 --> 00:03:33,349
But he was lying on a bed

61
00:03:36,683 --> 00:03:38,454
He asked me a
number of questions

62
00:03:38,974 --> 00:03:41,422
About my charge

63
00:03:41,474 --> 00:03:42,724
And I answered him

64
00:03:43,584 --> 00:03:44,651
After that they took
me back to the hall

65
00:03:46,969 --> 00:03:49,834
They brought me into a large hall
that had once been for weddings

66
00:03:51,500 --> 00:03:54,365
At the <i>Qaimaqam</i>, it
used to be a wedding hall

67
00:03:55,381 --> 00:03:57,776
Huge, over there

68
00:03:59,495 --> 00:04:02,568
I reckon it held
300 to 400 people

69
00:04:04,261 --> 00:04:05,407
A large hall

70
00:04:05,964 --> 00:04:08,855
With a stage for parties and
a spot for the bride and groom

71
00:04:08,880 --> 00:04:10,678
This hall was
turned into a prison

72
00:04:12,631 --> 00:04:16,667
So we stayed there, and whoever wanted to
walk could walk inside because it was so big

73
00:04:18,047 --> 00:04:19,974
They dressed us in
<i>dishdashas</i>, robes about this long

74
00:04:21,667 --> 00:04:25,625
At prayer time anyone who wanted to
do <i>wudu</i> [ablution] could go to the toilets

75
00:04:25,650 --> 00:04:27,709
There were three or four toilets

76
00:04:27,734 --> 00:04:29,818
Whoever went into the
toilets could take his time

77
00:04:31,428 --> 00:04:34,787
The <i>Hisba</i> [religious police] car
came and they took us out of there

78
00:04:35,620 --> 00:04:38,042
They put us in the <i>Hisba</i> vehicle
and brought us here afterward

79
00:04:42,495 --> 00:04:44,292
They brought us here
and I didn’t know the place

80
00:04:44,579 --> 00:04:47,964
They took me in through
here—there was a parking lot

81
00:04:48,901 --> 00:04:50,386
They had seized it

82
00:04:51,193 --> 00:04:53,146
We stood in the yard after they
unloaded us from the vehicle

83
00:04:53,745 --> 00:04:56,480
There were about seven to
eight of us when they brought us

84
00:04:56,505 --> 00:04:58,016
They had brought
people from another hall

85
00:04:58,771 --> 00:05:02,495
They made us enter with our heads lowered,
our hands shackled, and our eyes blindfolded

86
00:05:02,520 --> 00:05:04,058
They brought us
in through this door

87
00:05:04,631 --> 00:05:08,172
They led us from here and took
us up the stairs to the hall above

88
00:05:09,547 --> 00:05:12,646
I served my sentence in the hall

89
00:05:24,365 --> 00:05:26,057
Interviewer: When you
entered this courtyard

90
00:05:27,178 --> 00:05:30,381
Did you enter the yard and corridor
while your eyes were blindfolded?

91
00:05:31,422 --> 00:05:33,036
And your hands were shackled?

92
00:05:33,061 --> 00:05:39,391
If your eyes were blindfolded, what
sounds could you hear around you?

93
00:05:40,693 --> 00:05:44,261
They brought me in with my eyes
blindfolded and my hands shackled

94
00:05:45,157 --> 00:05:50,338
They took us in through here and I could
hear the sounds of flogging and their chatter

95
00:05:51,172 --> 00:05:52,865
But I didn’t know what
they were talking about

96
00:05:53,542 --> 00:05:58,151
The sound of cleaning weapons
and the click of their walkie-talkies

97
00:05:58,176 --> 00:05:59,349
Which they used to call with

98
00:06:00,260 --> 00:06:03,360
They made us go up a bit here,
then continued with us to the hall

99
00:06:03,568 --> 00:06:04,428
Interviewer: Okay

100
00:06:06,719 --> 00:06:11,172
Do you remember the ISIS members
present, their names and nationalities?

101
00:06:13,829 --> 00:06:14,974
Their appearance?

102
00:06:15,261 --> 00:06:16,823
They were all masked

103
00:06:17,526 --> 00:06:22,057
I don’t remember them or know
their names, they were all masked

104
00:06:22,082 --> 00:06:23,855
Even their hands weren’t visible

105
00:06:28,542 --> 00:06:30,938
Interviewer: Have you
heard about women’s cells?

106
00:06:30,963 --> 00:06:34,792
Or cells for ISIS members
being punished inside this prison?

107
00:06:36,198 --> 00:06:38,464
There weren’t any in this place.

108
00:06:38,959 --> 00:06:40,521
Interviewer: There
were no women’s cells?

109
00:06:41,094 --> 00:06:44,896
There were cells for women, but not
for ISIS members themselves.

110
00:06:46,355 --> 00:06:51,172
This room was for
women, and that room too.

111
00:06:52,214 --> 00:06:54,193
Interviewer: And the rest of the
rooms, do you recall their purpose?

112
00:06:54,454 --> 00:06:57,188
No, I only remember
there was a hall here.

113
00:06:58,047 --> 00:07:01,901
In this hall, for major charges.

114
00:07:02,553 --> 00:07:07,032
For example, someone was caught
with a Kia truck transporting cigarettes

115
00:07:08,172 --> 00:07:11,766
And other materials they
used to bring from outside Mosul

116
00:07:16,584 --> 00:07:21,583
Interviewer: Can you describe the sound
you heard from the women’s cells?

117
00:07:23,250 --> 00:07:25,230
I heard their children’s
voices, I mean

118
00:07:26,193 --> 00:07:27,678
Their children crying

119
00:07:28,980 --> 00:07:30,776
From that window over there

120
00:07:37,625 --> 00:07:40,803
Interviewer: Do you have a memory
related to this spot in this corridor?

121
00:07:40,828 --> 00:07:41,870
With ISIS?

122
00:07:43,511 --> 00:07:48,120
I only remember that I entered this place
normally and left with my hand amputated.

123
00:07:54,500 --> 00:07:58,615
Interviewer: Did you notice display
screens showing ISIS videos in this yard?

124
00:07:59,370 --> 00:08:03,303
No, in the yard there weren’t
any, only in their official’s room.

125
00:08:03,875 --> 00:08:05,308
There was a screen

126
00:08:05,437 --> 00:08:08,068
Interviewer: The sharia judge’s room?
Witness: Yes

127
00:08:14,750 --> 00:08:17,068
Interviewer: Regarding
the three cells you were in...

128
00:08:17,093 --> 00:08:19,151
How did you spend
your time in them

129
00:08:19,620 --> 00:08:22,719
Is there a particular memory
from those cells you can’t forget?

130
00:08:23,839 --> 00:08:27,250
How did you feel when
we walked in them?

131
00:08:28,786 --> 00:08:33,318
I felt that when I entered my hand
was there, and when I left it wasn’t

132
00:08:33,735 --> 00:08:35,115
I spent the time sleeping

133
00:08:35,662 --> 00:08:37,797
Only when prayer time came, I
prayed and went back to sleep

134
00:08:39,985 --> 00:08:43,995
Interviewer: How did
the ISIS jailers treat you?

135
00:08:44,020 --> 00:08:45,844
At prayer times...

136
00:08:45,869 --> 00:08:49,230
Did they act violently to
make you stand up for prayer?

137
00:08:49,407 --> 00:08:55,266
They came at prayer time and
knocked on the door, on the bars

138
00:08:56,594 --> 00:08:59,146
Shouting—It’s prayer
time, get up, pray, get up

139
00:08:59,980 --> 00:09:01,829
Interviewer: Did they supervise your performance of the prayer?
Witness: What do you mean?

140
00:09:03,521 --> 00:09:07,141
Interviewer: Meaning they came to
make sure you were praying and then left?

141
00:09:07,166 --> 00:09:08,756
Yes, one of them
stood at the door

142
00:09:09,511 --> 00:09:12,271
Everyone performed <i>wudu</i>
[ablution] and the prayer was collective

143
00:09:13,469 --> 00:09:15,995
They prayed and finished,
then each returned to his place

144
00:09:23,599 --> 00:09:27,401
Interviewer: What sounds did you
hear from inside the detention room?

145
00:09:27,740 --> 00:09:30,500
And how was the smell
of the three rooms?

146
00:09:31,709 --> 00:09:33,974
I mean, the smell wasn’t good

147
00:09:33,999 --> 00:09:36,526
And we heard the voices
of those they were flogging

148
00:09:36,551 --> 00:09:41,786
And the crying of those
children I talked about

149
00:09:41,811 --> 00:09:44,183
Whose mothers were
here and being flogged

150
00:09:46,552 --> 00:09:48,506
I mean, I heard many things

151
00:09:48,844 --> 00:09:49,990
And sounds

152
00:09:55,980 --> 00:09:58,531
Interviewer: Was
the talk between you

153
00:09:58,556 --> 00:10:02,099
Or talk in general, was it
forbidden inside the cell?

154
00:10:02,124 --> 00:10:04,000
Between you and
the prisoners with you?

155
00:10:04,599 --> 00:10:05,927
No, no, it wasn't forbidden

156
00:10:06,631 --> 00:10:08,740
We would talk and chat

157
00:10:09,498 --> 00:10:13,248
But only a little

158
00:10:14,082 --> 00:10:16,165
We couldn't talk
about other things

159
00:10:16,946 --> 00:10:18,795
Only about prayer matters

160
00:10:21,009 --> 00:10:24,550
Anyone who wanted to
learn the prayer and its details

161
00:10:28,457 --> 00:10:30,905
Interviewer: Until what
hour did you talk together

162
00:10:30,930 --> 00:10:33,873
Did they come tell
you to stop and sleep?

163
00:10:33,898 --> 00:10:36,165
Or was it okay to
talk at other times?

164
00:10:36,451 --> 00:10:40,436
At night after the prayer

165
00:10:40,879 --> 00:10:42,832
We chatted, then the
jailer came and yelled

166
00:10:42,857 --> 00:10:45,332
Enough, it's time to sleep

167
00:10:45,357 --> 00:10:46,530
And everyone slept

168
00:10:46,555 --> 00:10:49,472
No one stayed
awake—lights off, all slept

169
00:10:50,490 --> 00:10:55,828
If they heard anyone
talking or making a sound

170
00:10:56,115 --> 00:10:57,079
They would come up immediately

171
00:10:58,303 --> 00:11:01,115
They knocked—Who was
shouting? Who spoke?

172
00:11:02,521 --> 00:11:04,240
They checked,
then went back down

173
00:11:09,787 --> 00:11:12,469
I only remember someone
standing here with a sword

174
00:11:12,964 --> 00:11:14,162
I looked at him from above

175
00:11:14,969 --> 00:11:16,428
He was standing
here, in this spot

176
00:11:18,250 --> 00:11:19,709
That's what I remember

177
00:11:20,204 --> 00:11:21,584
It never leaves my mind

178
00:11:23,615 --> 00:11:25,308
Interviewer: What
did that man look like?

179
00:11:25,333 --> 00:11:26,558
He was huge and masked;
you couldn't see his face

180
00:11:28,032 --> 00:11:32,329
Even his hands were
hidden because of tattoos

181
00:11:32,641 --> 00:11:33,995
So no one would recognize him

182
00:11:40,662 --> 00:11:46,105
It was Ramadan—at <i>suhoor</i> we
got <i>samoon</i> [finger roll] and tahini

183
00:11:46,547 --> 00:11:48,162
The <i>samoon</i> bread was stale

184
00:11:49,047 --> 00:11:51,365
It crumbled when you held it

185
00:11:52,355 --> 00:11:54,047
And they brought the tahini dip

186
00:11:55,428 --> 00:11:56,599
And a pot of tea

187
00:11:57,563 --> 00:12:00,089
Everyone ate <i>suhoor</i>,
prayed, and slept

188
00:12:01,053 --> 00:12:04,985
At <i>iftar</i> they brought soup

189
00:12:05,558 --> 00:12:07,537
Or rice, or bulgur

190
00:12:07,901 --> 00:12:08,943
That's the food

191
00:12:09,089 --> 00:12:11,355
Interviewer: And was everyone forced to fast?
Witness: Yes

192
00:12:12,084 --> 00:12:13,933
Anyone who didn't
fast was punished

193
00:12:14,688 --> 00:12:16,146
And anyone who didn't pray too

194
00:12:17,657 --> 00:12:19,375
Even long pants got you punished

195
00:12:20,365 --> 00:12:22,526
Interviewer: Punished while inside the cell?
Witness: Yes

196
00:12:27,839 --> 00:12:31,980
Interviewer: Were the <i>iftar</i>
and <i>suhoor</i> meals in Ramadan

197
00:12:32,005 --> 00:12:34,037
Enough and filling?

198
00:12:35,547 --> 00:12:39,245
Half the people didn't eat
because it wasn't enough

199
00:12:39,584 --> 00:12:44,323
They brought a small
pot for 70 to 80 people

200
00:12:44,348 --> 00:12:45,157
So who would it be enough for?

201
00:12:45,755 --> 00:12:47,297
It isn't only one or two people

202
00:12:48,443 --> 00:12:51,047
Interviewer: Seventy to eighty people inside each room?
Witness: Yes

203
00:12:51,803 --> 00:12:52,792
So who would it be enough for?

204
00:12:53,469 --> 00:12:57,245
They brought a small pot, threw it by the
door, turned their backs, and walked away

205
00:12:58,625 --> 00:13:01,542
From their own food and drink

206
00:13:02,193 --> 00:13:07,010
Interviewer: When you were inside the room,
you mentioned there were many jars of tahini

207
00:13:07,167 --> 00:13:10,579
Were all the jars in your room

208
00:13:10,604 --> 00:13:15,136
They used to
bring five to six jars

209
00:13:15,631 --> 00:13:16,803
And distribute them to the rooms

210
00:13:18,131 --> 00:13:22,911
So whoever got hungry
would take some and eat

211
00:13:23,745 --> 00:13:29,162
And when it was time for
iftar and they brought the food

212
00:13:30,047 --> 00:13:31,844
They would eat,
finish, and then sit

213
00:13:31,869 --> 00:13:35,230
And at night, whoever
was hungry or hadn't eaten

214
00:13:35,646 --> 00:13:37,730
Would eat tahini,
<i>samoon</i>, and tea

215
00:13:40,698 --> 00:13:44,553
Interviewer: Was the food
they brought clean and healthy?

216
00:13:44,813 --> 00:13:46,506
Or was it, for
example, old and stale?

217
00:13:47,469 --> 00:13:50,776
It was the leftovers
of their own food

218
00:13:51,297 --> 00:13:53,980
From what they ate themselves

219
00:13:55,016 --> 00:13:56,891
They brought the
leftovers up to us

220
00:14:02,438 --> 00:14:07,256
Interviewer: Did you notice any
obvious diseases among the prisoners?

221
00:14:07,620 --> 00:14:11,526
They didn’t complain, but did
you see anyone with itching or lice?

222
00:14:12,803 --> 00:14:17,594
Anyone in pain or suffering
from an illness, like a fever

223
00:14:18,896 --> 00:14:23,141
No, there was no illness at
all, no scabies or anything else

224
00:14:25,667 --> 00:14:27,907
Interviewer: Was there any medical care for you?
Witness: No

225
00:14:27,932 --> 00:14:29,417
There was absolutely
no medical care

226
00:14:32,698 --> 00:14:37,776
Interviewer: If you asked
for more food or health care

227
00:14:37,801 --> 00:14:39,964
Or for clean water

228
00:14:39,989 --> 00:14:41,969
Interviewer: Did they respond to you?
Witness: No

229
00:14:43,011 --> 00:14:46,162
We drank water from the toilets

230
00:14:46,839 --> 00:14:49,365
We filled it and
drank from there

231
00:14:54,834 --> 00:15:01,032
There were all ages,
boys fifteen to twenty

232
00:15:01,057 --> 00:15:05,588
And elderly men, like the one
arrested for assaulting a woman

233
00:15:05,613 --> 00:15:08,219
Some had fired guns

234
00:15:08,271 --> 00:15:09,990
Another was there
over cigarettes

235
00:15:10,303 --> 00:15:11,787
And another for a
mobile phone charge

236
00:15:12,620 --> 00:15:14,808
There were many charges inside

237
00:15:18,469 --> 00:15:22,610
Interviewer: How were the relations
in the three cells you stayed in...

238
00:15:22,635 --> 00:15:24,485
In each one for a
few days at a time?

239
00:15:24,510 --> 00:15:27,297
How did you see the
relationships among the prisoners?

240
00:15:27,322 --> 00:15:30,136
Were their relationships good?

241
00:15:30,161 --> 00:15:33,521
Was there help among them,
did they talk to one another?

242
00:15:34,042 --> 00:15:37,531
There was some
talking but not much

243
00:15:38,521 --> 00:15:40,552
They could ask
about certain things

244
00:15:41,516 --> 00:15:43,677
About the charges and
reasons for detention

245
00:15:44,719 --> 00:15:46,985
Or whether you had
been before the judge

246
00:15:47,089 --> 00:15:49,224
What they had done to you
and what they would do

247
00:15:49,249 --> 00:15:50,943
And whether the judge
had spoken to you or not

248
00:15:52,011 --> 00:15:53,938
That kind of question

249
00:15:55,912 --> 00:15:59,636
Interviewer: Did ISIS plant any spies
among you in these three rooms?

250
00:15:59,661 --> 00:16:00,703
No

251
00:16:03,308 --> 00:16:06,954
Interviewer: Did any of your
companions die here or get tortured?

252
00:16:07,136 --> 00:16:11,901
Do you recall a name—someone
you heard was tortured and later died...

253
00:16:11,926 --> 00:16:14,844
Or was tortured, died, and
never returned to the cell?

254
00:16:15,782 --> 00:16:17,318
No, no, none

255
00:16:17,343 --> 00:16:22,032
They took someone out on a
theft charge, stealing a motorcycle

256
00:16:23,516 --> 00:16:28,724
They took him down, flogged him,
then brought him back to the hall

257
00:16:29,688 --> 00:16:33,385
Two days later they removed
him—they did nothing else to him

258
00:16:34,349 --> 00:16:38,516
Interviewer: How did you receive him
when he came back from the torture room...

259
00:16:38,541 --> 00:16:39,688
Flogged?

260
00:16:39,974 --> 00:16:41,589
Did you take care of him?

261
00:16:41,614 --> 00:16:44,740
Yes, I and two
others looked after him

262
00:16:46,355 --> 00:16:47,969
We cared for him

263
00:16:47,995 --> 00:16:52,162
His back was almost
black from the torture

264
00:16:53,881 --> 00:16:56,537
We comforted him,
saying, You’ll get out later

265
00:16:56,562 --> 00:17:00,209
And this beating is better
than having your hand cut off

266
00:17:00,730 --> 00:17:04,766
We encouraged him—he rested and
slept, and next day they took him out

267
00:17:09,834 --> 00:17:12,256
Regarding ISIS videos,
did they show you any?

268
00:17:12,709 --> 00:17:15,860
Did they gather you
and make you watch?

269
00:17:15,885 --> 00:17:18,178
Their execution videos

270
00:17:18,203 --> 00:17:19,480
Or hand amputations

271
00:17:19,532 --> 00:17:22,969
If they showed them,
how did you feel?

272
00:17:24,506 --> 00:17:25,651
No one could speak

273
00:17:25,704 --> 00:17:29,662
They made us watch things
outside, not in the prison

274
00:17:30,651 --> 00:17:34,584
They gathered people and
showed how they amputated hands

275
00:17:34,609 --> 00:17:35,834
Or stoned people

276
00:17:36,355 --> 00:17:38,412
And threw them off buildings

277
00:17:39,011 --> 00:17:42,344
We saw all of that because
our house was in Dawasa

278
00:17:42,683 --> 00:17:46,016
When they threw
people, I could see them

279
00:17:46,563 --> 00:17:48,594
I also saw the stonings

280
00:17:49,454 --> 00:17:51,797
And the hand amputations too

281
00:17:52,422 --> 00:17:56,198
They forced people
to gather and watch

282
00:17:56,223 --> 00:17:58,334
They did it in the street
so people would gather

283
00:17:58,933 --> 00:18:01,927
So aircraft wouldn’t
spot and bomb them

284
00:18:04,714 --> 00:18:08,959
Interviewer: At age
fifteen, a minor child

285
00:18:09,219 --> 00:18:11,849
Forced to see these
scenes every day

286
00:18:11,927 --> 00:18:13,829
Right at your doorstep

287
00:18:13,854 --> 00:18:20,495
That tall Orzdi Bak building
they pushed people off

288
00:18:20,520 --> 00:18:22,136
A famous building in Mosul

289
00:18:22,683 --> 00:18:24,714
How did you feel
at that young age?

290
00:18:27,292 --> 00:18:28,881
Well, honestly

291
00:18:30,990 --> 00:18:34,089
Absolutely no one
could talk to them

292
00:18:34,412 --> 00:18:37,562
They gathered crowds—why
did they do it in the street?

293
00:18:37,823 --> 00:18:39,594
So everyone would gather

294
00:18:39,803 --> 00:18:41,964
And it would be
a lesson to others

295
00:18:42,980 --> 00:18:47,849
When they amputated my
hand, it was to warn the rest

296
00:18:48,110 --> 00:18:49,620
So no one would do it

297
00:18:49,750 --> 00:18:51,131
Or would fear doing it

298
00:18:51,625 --> 00:18:54,308
They did it in the
street to scare people

299
00:18:54,750 --> 00:18:57,094
To terrify children and women

300
00:19:02,771 --> 00:19:04,438
Interviewer: While
you were in this prison

301
00:19:05,428 --> 00:19:09,412
Was this prison shelled
while you were inside?

302
00:19:09,437 --> 00:19:11,808
Did they leave you
alone at night and go out?

303
00:19:11,833 --> 00:19:14,724
Because they feared an
airstrike so they wouldn't die

304
00:19:15,396 --> 00:19:19,693
At night only a
few people stayed

305
00:19:21,125 --> 00:19:22,401
Three to four people

306
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:24,849
And the rest all
left, they didn't stay

307
00:19:25,605 --> 00:19:29,172
A small number stayed so
the place wouldn't be empty

308
00:19:29,641 --> 00:19:31,516
So no one could mess with them

309
00:19:32,271 --> 00:19:36,646
As for the rest

310
00:19:36,671 --> 00:19:40,500
The senior officials didn't
stay in the same place

311
00:19:40,525 --> 00:19:41,803
They were afraid
it might be bombed

312
00:19:42,245 --> 00:19:45,240
When we were here there
was no shelling on this prison

313
00:19:45,849 --> 00:19:49,053
They didn't stay here—they
were afraid and went elsewhere

314
00:19:50,094 --> 00:19:52,933
They hid in houses
among families

315
00:19:53,297 --> 00:19:54,495
And in shops

316
00:19:54,520 --> 00:19:55,589
That's how it was

317
00:20:01,370 --> 00:20:05,980
Interviewer: Did you or any of your
companions try to escape from the prison?

318
00:20:06,500 --> 00:20:07,803
I wanted to escape

319
00:20:09,391 --> 00:20:11,266
I reached the side of the door

320
00:20:11,865 --> 00:20:14,261
With a small move I could
have opened it and escaped

321
00:20:14,286 --> 00:20:17,881
But fearing they would kill
me, I stayed and didn't escape

322
00:20:19,026 --> 00:20:22,724
Interviewer: If you had known your
fate and the sentence you would receive

323
00:20:22,749 --> 00:20:24,448
Would you have escaped?

324
00:20:24,473 --> 00:20:26,557
Yes I would have escaped and not stayed

325
00:20:34,422 --> 00:20:36,974
Showering happened
every three to four days

326
00:20:38,250 --> 00:20:39,943
There was no shampoo, only soap

327
00:20:40,672 --> 00:20:43,224
And no scrubber or towel

328
00:20:44,448 --> 00:20:46,532
Whoever showered

329
00:20:47,417 --> 00:20:50,073
Finished and put on his clothes
in the bathroom while still wet

330
00:20:50,098 --> 00:20:51,506
He put on his
clothes and went out

331
00:20:53,224 --> 00:20:56,428
The bathrooms were for anyone
who needed to relieve himself and so on

332
00:20:57,912 --> 00:20:59,370
Very few things

333
00:20:59,813 --> 00:21:02,547
Because someone sat
next to the bathroom door

334
00:21:02,572 --> 00:21:05,193
So the foul smell reached them

335
00:21:05,218 --> 00:21:08,109
The smell reached the
last room, the third room

336
00:21:08,657 --> 00:21:11,964
So only a few went
to the bathroom

337
00:21:13,214 --> 00:21:15,454
Interviewer: Did you
take turns cleaning it?

338
00:21:15,479 --> 00:21:16,808
Yes we cleaned it

339
00:21:17,823 --> 00:21:19,646
Interviewer: Did that
lessen the odor in the place?

340
00:21:21,105 --> 00:21:22,485
No, it made no difference

341
00:21:26,469 --> 00:21:29,256
Interviewer: Were you harassed
by the prisoners who were with you

342
00:21:29,281 --> 00:21:30,844
When you used the toilet?

343
00:21:32,459 --> 00:21:33,266
Yes

344
00:21:33,943 --> 00:21:37,693
Interviewer: What happened?
What did they bother you about?

345
00:21:39,568 --> 00:21:42,588
I wanted to shower

346
00:21:43,214 --> 00:21:46,990
And one prisoner was inside

347
00:21:49,099 --> 00:21:51,000
He said, Why do
you shower daily?

348
00:21:51,025 --> 00:21:53,422
And the water splashes onto us

349
00:21:53,447 --> 00:21:55,870
We sleep here at the
door and you don't care

350
00:21:55,895 --> 00:21:58,396
You sit at the other end

351
00:21:59,178 --> 00:22:00,584
He kept talking

352
00:22:00,766 --> 00:22:02,042
So I didn’t speak
then, I remained silent

353
00:22:02,526 --> 00:22:04,193
To avoid trouble

354
00:22:04,896 --> 00:22:07,136
Otherwise they’d take
us out and beat us outside

355
00:22:07,709 --> 00:22:11,250
So I stayed silent and didn’t speak, and he kept
talking alone until he’d finished and then he fell silent

356
00:22:15,079 --> 00:22:17,057
Interviewer: Some
of the people we met

357
00:22:17,082 --> 00:22:19,662
Said they would
go to the washrooms

358
00:22:20,040 --> 00:22:22,514
They’d use the toilet
or go to the showers

359
00:22:22,801 --> 00:22:25,457
Just to get some
time to themselves

360
00:22:25,822 --> 00:22:28,556
Away from the prison
atmosphere and the other prisoners

361
00:22:28,581 --> 00:22:31,681
Away from the atmosphere of fear

362
00:22:32,020 --> 00:22:36,447
So did you do that to feel
some privacy with yourself?

363
00:22:37,150 --> 00:22:41,316
Nothing like that, at the
end of the day it’s a prison

364
00:22:42,358 --> 00:22:47,280
Even if someone goes into
the bathroom, he’s still in prison

365
00:22:48,712 --> 00:22:50,483
That bathroom is
in the prison

366
00:22:51,212 --> 00:22:55,509
A person doesn’t leave the
cell and go somewhere else

367
00:22:55,952 --> 00:22:57,150
It’s in the same cell

368
00:23:03,756 --> 00:23:05,553
They came up to us

369
00:23:05,735 --> 00:23:09,276
They said anyone under
16 years old should come out

370
00:23:09,667 --> 00:23:11,308
He’ll be released, he won’t stay

371
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:18,833
I went out along with
three or four others

372
00:23:20,110 --> 00:23:24,511
They took us down from
upstairs with our eyes blindfolded

373
00:23:25,761 --> 00:23:28,339
They led us down these
stairs and up from here

374
00:23:30,891 --> 00:23:33,860
There were civilians standing

375
00:23:34,276 --> 00:23:35,162
Prisoners too

376
00:23:35,735 --> 00:23:39,693
Each person went in to
see the judge separately

377
00:23:40,834 --> 00:23:44,428
The judge questioned him, then
they flogged him and released him

378
00:23:46,329 --> 00:23:47,917
My turn came and I went in

379
00:23:48,308 --> 00:23:50,026
He asked me–What’s
your charge? I said–Theft

380
00:23:50,808 --> 00:23:54,558
He said–Motorcycle theft?
I said, No, house theft

381
00:23:55,495 --> 00:23:56,771
It was written on it
that it was confiscated

382
00:23:58,099 --> 00:24:01,120
He told them—Return this one, the
sentence will be carried out on him

383
00:24:02,006 --> 00:24:04,037
Interviewer: Did he say that in front of you?
Witness: Yes

384
00:24:05,730 --> 00:24:07,240
They took me back and
took me upstairs to the room

385
00:24:07,265 --> 00:24:10,287
Interviewer: And when you went
back upstairs, did you know your fate?

386
00:24:11,016 --> 00:24:12,787
Since you hadn’t been
released from prison

387
00:24:12,891 --> 00:24:14,766
He gave me hope
by taking me upstairs

388
00:24:15,234 --> 00:24:17,292
What I understood was
that he would cut off my hand

389
00:24:17,490 --> 00:24:18,688
He took me upstairs

390
00:24:19,079 --> 00:24:22,855
Two of them came to us, and we
were three or four prisoners there

391
00:24:23,245 --> 00:24:25,823
When they took us out, but
those had different charges

392
00:24:27,438 --> 00:24:30,433
They came to us and said...

393
00:24:30,927 --> 00:24:34,391
The judge felt sorry for you
when he saw that only you were left

394
00:24:34,599 --> 00:24:36,006
So he will release you

395
00:24:36,031 --> 00:24:37,490
He pardoned you
and will let you out

396
00:24:37,803 --> 00:24:39,235
But don’t do again what you did

397
00:24:40,485 --> 00:24:43,011
So I and those with me
cried with joy

398
00:24:44,678 --> 00:24:47,204
It was six o’clock at
sunset, during Ramadan

399
00:24:48,245 --> 00:24:51,995
So I started thinking to myself that I
would leave here and go to my family’s house

400
00:24:52,178 --> 00:24:54,209
Where I would eat and
break the fast with them

401
00:24:56,344 --> 00:25:00,120
They left us, everyone
left and only we stayed here

402
00:25:00,145 --> 00:25:02,073
In this prison, everyone left

403
00:25:04,261 --> 00:25:06,266
Then it became <i>Laylat al-Qadr</i>

404
00:25:08,557 --> 00:25:11,787
They came to us
and said—Let’s go

405
00:25:11,812 --> 00:25:13,792
We’ll take you out

406
00:25:15,381 --> 00:25:17,698
They blindfolded our eyes,
shackled our hands, and took us out

407
00:25:17,723 --> 00:25:18,896
Interviewer: What
time was it then?

408
00:25:19,651 --> 00:25:22,750
They took us out at six
o’clock, around sunset

409
00:25:24,261 --> 00:25:26,683
They took us out
and I was barefoot

410
00:25:27,151 --> 00:25:29,000
Barefoot, without shoes

411
00:25:31,396 --> 00:25:34,521
They took us out and
put us in a Hisba vehicle

412
00:25:35,303 --> 00:25:39,026
And they put a cannula—a
tourniquet—on my hand

413
00:25:39,521 --> 00:25:41,839
When they put the cannula on my
hand I knew they would cut off my hand

414
00:25:41,864 --> 00:25:43,375
Interviewer: You and those with you?
Witness: Yes

415
00:25:44,053 --> 00:25:45,537
They put the cannula on my hand

416
00:25:45,562 --> 00:25:48,636
Interviewer: Who was the person
responsible for this?

417
00:25:48,661 --> 00:25:50,042
Who put the
Cannulas and the tourniquets on?

418
00:25:50,067 --> 00:25:51,917
Did they put them on
you in the vehicle?

419
00:25:51,942 --> 00:25:55,276
Did they talk to you? Didn’t you ask
them why they were putting cannulas on you?

420
00:25:55,381 --> 00:25:58,375
As for me, when they put
the cannula on my hand

421
00:25:58,974 --> 00:26:01,448
I didn’t know why

422
00:26:01,839 --> 00:26:05,719
I said, Uncle, are you going to cut off my
hand? He said, No, uncle, we won’t cut your hand

423
00:26:05,823 --> 00:26:07,438
We will only take
you to the hospital

424
00:26:08,219 --> 00:26:10,849
When they put the cannula on my
hand I knew they would cut off my hand

425
00:26:12,151 --> 00:26:14,313
Then one of them called out

426
00:26:14,338 --> 00:26:17,594
He told him—Stay here with them,
I’ll go get something and come back

427
00:26:18,818 --> 00:26:20,641
He went to get the
things and came back

428
00:26:22,256 --> 00:26:24,365
And what were the
things he brought!?

429
00:26:25,355 --> 00:26:26,422
He brought rubber tubing

430
00:26:27,464 --> 00:26:29,704
He ties it here on the arm

431
00:26:30,433 --> 00:26:33,297
He tightens it on the
arm here and ties it here

432
00:26:33,688 --> 00:26:34,964
He placed it at this spot

433
00:26:35,303 --> 00:26:36,891
So the blood would stop

434
00:26:38,714 --> 00:26:40,563
So blood wouldn’t
flow when they cut it

435
00:26:41,209 --> 00:26:45,010
He placed the cannula and injected
me through it, and I couldn’t feel it

436
00:26:45,922 --> 00:26:48,318
I sat and moved it on the
ground like this and couldn’t feel it

437
00:26:48,422 --> 00:26:50,141
I pinched it and
still couldn’t feel it

438
00:26:52,797 --> 00:26:57,641
They took us out and took
us to the Cairo neighborhood

439
00:26:59,230 --> 00:27:00,766
They took us to the
Cairo neighborhood

440
00:27:03,657 --> 00:27:09,490
They got out and unloaded the
loudspeakers, the device, and the generator

441
00:27:11,131 --> 00:27:15,714
They started calling on their
loudspeaker and gathered the people

442
00:27:16,391 --> 00:27:18,605
They took us down from the
vehicle and sat us on the curb

443
00:27:20,141 --> 00:27:22,172
They started talking
to us and so on

444
00:27:23,761 --> 00:27:28,943
And at the moment they
were going to cut off our hands

445
00:27:29,750 --> 00:27:30,870
Interviewer: What did
they talk to you about?

446
00:27:31,521 --> 00:27:33,006
It was ISIS itself

447
00:27:33,031 --> 00:27:34,386
Interviewer: When they
got you out of the car

448
00:27:34,411 --> 00:27:37,433
When they took us out they
told us to sit and not move

449
00:27:39,334 --> 00:27:43,422
When it became certain
they would cut off our hands

450
00:27:43,969 --> 00:27:47,432
Then he came and pulled
me, but how did he pull me?

451
00:27:47,457 --> 00:27:50,480
He yanked me with force

452
00:27:51,651 --> 00:27:52,797
He said—Come, stand

453
00:27:53,886 --> 00:27:56,256
But I stayed scared and seated

454
00:27:56,568 --> 00:27:59,198
He grabbed me here, told
me–Stand, and he made me stand

455
00:28:00,318 --> 00:28:03,938
He sat me on the chair

456
00:28:03,963 --> 00:28:05,787
And he brought a
table and set it there

457
00:28:07,167 --> 00:28:08,730
And they tied my
hand with a rope here

458
00:28:09,459 --> 00:28:11,881
Three or four of them grabbed
me here by the shoulders

459
00:28:11,906 --> 00:28:13,261
And one of them held me here

460
00:28:13,286 --> 00:28:14,667
And another grabbed me here

461
00:28:15,110 --> 00:28:17,401
And one of them stood in
front of me behind the table

462
00:28:17,948 --> 00:28:20,162
He kept pulling my hand with
the rope until it would tear off

463
00:28:21,906 --> 00:28:25,266
He brought a cleaver and
placed another cleaver on top of it

464
00:28:25,422 --> 00:28:27,480
With a single blow it
was severed instantly

465
00:28:27,781 --> 00:28:29,318
Interviewer: Did you feel it?
Witness: No

466
00:28:30,203 --> 00:28:32,417
After that they wrapped my hand
in cloth and put me into the car

467
00:28:32,677 --> 00:28:36,453
When they put me in the car, they
removed the blindfold from my eyes

468
00:28:39,448 --> 00:28:41,583
Interviewer: What about the
two people who were with you?

469
00:28:42,391 --> 00:28:45,854
They also amputated
one man's hand

470
00:28:45,879 --> 00:28:47,912
They took him with me
to the hospital as well

471
00:28:48,485 --> 00:28:50,073
They placed us in the hospital

472
00:28:51,115 --> 00:28:55,177
The other one whose leg they
cut—I don't know where they took him

473
00:28:55,750 --> 00:28:58,849
They brought him with us to the
place where they amputated our hands

474
00:28:59,396 --> 00:29:02,964
But I don't know—after they cut off our hands,
they took us in one car and he went in another

475
00:29:03,745 --> 00:29:05,099
They went and amputated
his leg somewhere else

476
00:29:06,542 --> 00:29:10,657
Interviewer: Were you the only one whose sentence
was carried out in the Cairo neighborhood?

477
00:29:10,682 --> 00:29:12,428
Yes, plus another person with
me but on a different charge

478
00:29:13,339 --> 00:29:15,474
I mean, his charge
wasn't the same as mine

479
00:29:15,683 --> 00:29:17,271
Interviewer: Did they carry
out your sentence before his?

480
00:29:17,584 --> 00:29:19,459
I was the first person whose
sentence was carried out

481
00:29:20,865 --> 00:29:25,969
Interviewer: It was close to iftar
time—was there a crowd of people?

482
00:29:26,438 --> 00:29:27,349
Yes

483
00:29:28,235 --> 00:29:31,047
Interviewer: What did you see in
front of you upon your first arrival?

484
00:29:32,271 --> 00:29:33,963
You mean when they
amputated my hand?

485
00:29:33,988 --> 00:29:35,735
Interviewer: Yes, when
you reached the place?

486
00:29:36,230 --> 00:29:40,605
People were busy buying what
they needed from the market

487
00:29:40,630 --> 00:29:41,776
It was a public market

488
00:29:42,834 --> 00:29:46,349
They were buying from
clothing shops and other stores

489
00:29:48,042 --> 00:29:50,672
So when they saw
the Hisba vehicle stop

490
00:29:51,323 --> 00:29:54,344
And when they unloaded the items, people
knew a sentence was about to be carried out

491
00:29:56,427 --> 00:29:59,657
People gathered little by little

492
00:29:59,682 --> 00:30:02,756
Until there were a lot of people, and
they carried out the sentence on us

493
00:30:05,542 --> 00:30:08,771
Interviewer: During that time were you
crying and begging them to let you go?

494
00:30:08,796 --> 00:30:11,766
And were you talking to
them, or were you resigned?

495
00:30:12,157 --> 00:30:15,438
There was no way
back then–I surrendered

496
00:30:16,193 --> 00:30:18,849
There was nothing
at all to stop them

497
00:30:20,125 --> 00:30:23,849
Once they made a decision, there
was no turning back—they'd carry it out

498
00:30:24,526 --> 00:30:25,933
I was scared and sitting then

499
00:30:25,958 --> 00:30:27,062
Sitting on the curb

500
00:30:30,317 --> 00:30:32,296
Interviewer: Didn't you try to run away?
Witness: No

501
00:30:33,078 --> 00:30:35,369
Because they were all
gathered in the same place

502
00:30:35,838 --> 00:30:38,833
And here, in our
community, I mean

503
00:30:39,744 --> 00:30:40,812
While ISIS was present

504
00:30:42,895 --> 00:30:44,926
They called them
<i>lawkiyya</i>, their hypocrites

505
00:30:45,135 --> 00:30:46,932
Anyone who tried to escape

506
00:30:47,479 --> 00:30:50,916
People would catch
him and not let him flee

507
00:30:52,479 --> 00:30:53,833
That’s why I didn’t

508
00:30:56,255 --> 00:30:58,390
Interviewer: Were your family there?
Witness: No

509
00:30:58,415 --> 00:30:59,874
My family didn’t know about it

510
00:30:59,899 --> 00:31:03,416
My family didn’t know because I had sent
them word that I would get out safely

511
00:31:04,536 --> 00:31:08,130
Interviewer: What was the situation
in the hospital, who was there?

512
00:31:08,224 --> 00:31:11,245
They didn’t know until I
went to them at home myself

513
00:31:17,142 --> 00:31:20,033
They cut off our hands
and put us in a car

514
00:31:20,111 --> 00:31:21,882
They brought us
to Saddam Hospital

515
00:31:22,663 --> 00:31:23,861
Salam Hospital

516
00:31:25,345 --> 00:31:26,517
They let us out

517
00:31:28,184 --> 00:31:32,428
The first person was taken to the operating
room, his hand was stitched, and he was sent out

518
00:31:33,314 --> 00:31:35,736
I was the second person
to enter the operating room

519
00:31:38,001 --> 00:31:42,038
He asked me, do you have any
illnesses or allergies? I said, no

520
00:31:42,063 --> 00:31:43,210
The doctor was asking me

521
00:31:43,653 --> 00:31:44,876
I told him, no, I
don’t have any of that

522
00:31:46,231 --> 00:31:48,861
He said to me—Sit here, so I sat

523
00:31:49,844 --> 00:31:50,990
Then he said again, No, stand

524
00:31:51,355 --> 00:31:53,230
I stood, and he laid
me on a hospital bed

525
00:31:54,167 --> 00:31:55,860
He put a cannula in my hand

526
00:31:57,058 --> 00:32:00,469
I don’t know what he injected
me with—seconds later I felt nothing

527
00:32:01,276 --> 00:32:04,271
When I opened my eyes,
I found my hand bandaged

528
00:32:04,296 --> 00:32:05,495
Interviewer: You lost consciousness?
Witness: Yes

529
00:32:06,250 --> 00:32:07,709
When I woke up

530
00:32:09,844 --> 00:32:11,172
I found my hand bandaged

531
00:32:11,197 --> 00:32:15,339
I thought to myself, could it be they are
tricking us and didn’t really cut off our hands

532
00:32:17,292 --> 00:32:19,454
When I became a little more
aware, I measured my hands together

533
00:32:19,479 --> 00:32:23,125
And when I saw one was shorter, I knew
they had cut off my hand and I started crying

534
00:32:26,344 --> 00:32:28,687
They gave me a booklet

535
00:32:31,370 --> 00:32:35,172
I don’t know what was written in
it—right-hand amputation and so on

536
00:32:35,797 --> 00:32:37,542
I took it and I still
keep it to this day

537
00:32:39,261 --> 00:32:40,849
And they gave me slippers

538
00:32:43,297 --> 00:32:47,959
And they gave me injections to treat
my hand, and said I had to take them

539
00:32:49,365 --> 00:32:50,303
I left

540
00:32:51,474 --> 00:32:52,984
They took us out of the hospital

541
00:32:54,313 --> 00:32:55,954
They left— they
brought us and then left

542
00:32:55,979 --> 00:32:57,792
Only one of them stayed
with us until we woke up

543
00:32:57,817 --> 00:32:59,485
He gave us these
booklets and left

544
00:33:00,761 --> 00:33:05,526
We left the hospital, and
at the door I hired a taxi

545
00:33:07,610 --> 00:33:11,646
He asked me–Where do you want me
to take you? I said, to the Dawasa area

546
00:33:13,209 --> 00:33:15,240
He said–Where exactly in Dawasa? I
told him, by the governorate building

547
00:33:17,454 --> 00:33:21,204
The man I rode with, I didn’t know
him, but he was my father’s friend

548
00:33:24,625 --> 00:33:27,933
When we left the hospital, he started
asking me what had happened and so on

549
00:33:27,958 --> 00:33:30,563
So I told him my story

550
00:33:31,136 --> 00:33:32,985
The taxi driver started crying

551
00:33:34,183 --> 00:33:35,381
He drove me home

552
00:33:35,745 --> 00:33:37,047
And I had no money with me

553
00:33:37,072 --> 00:33:39,495
I said to him—Wait a moment
so I can bring you the fare

554
00:33:39,782 --> 00:33:43,167
He said—No, no, I don't want it,
this is from me, a reward for God

555
00:33:46,240 --> 00:33:49,521
When I stepped out of the
car, I saw my older brother

556
00:33:51,917 --> 00:33:55,433
He said to me—Younes, what happened
to your hand?" I told him—They cut it off

557
00:33:56,943 --> 00:33:59,938
He didn’t stop, he started
crying and ran toward the house

558
00:34:01,553 --> 00:34:06,422
While running home he
shouted—Mom, Mom, Younes has come

559
00:34:08,662 --> 00:34:09,625
My mother was overjoyed

560
00:34:10,094 --> 00:34:14,391
And my father came, and she told him—Hajji,
didn’t I tell you he’d return safe

561
00:34:14,730 --> 00:34:16,214
Because that young man came
and told us he’d be released

562
00:34:17,463 --> 00:34:19,704
My brother told them—They
freed him, but they’ve cut off his hand

563
00:34:21,526 --> 00:34:23,401
At that moment my father
began hitting his head

564
00:34:25,797 --> 00:34:27,881
As for my mother, I
don’t know what to tell you

565
00:34:29,886 --> 00:34:31,214
Thank God in any case

566
00:34:34,625 --> 00:34:36,370
And that’s my story

567
00:34:46,579 --> 00:34:50,719
After I left prison I didn’t step outside
the house for about a year and a half

568
00:34:51,657 --> 00:34:52,829
I was ashamed in front of people

569
00:34:54,365 --> 00:34:56,370
People don’t know the truth

570
00:34:56,995 --> 00:35:01,683
Even my uncle,
my mother’s brother

571
00:35:02,230 --> 00:35:04,130
Says to me—If you hadn’t done something,
they wouldn’t have cut off your hand

572
00:35:06,006 --> 00:35:08,323
So what will strangers say

573
00:35:09,105 --> 00:35:10,849
For that reason

574
00:35:10,874 --> 00:35:15,172
I didn’t even mix with my
brothers and sisters at home

575
00:35:15,641 --> 00:35:17,542
I went out and came back alone

576
00:35:19,521 --> 00:35:21,553
In the days of ISIS, when
there were no cell phones

577
00:35:22,047 --> 00:35:29,156
At that time I desperately wanted
some relief, I was looking for ease

578
00:35:29,625 --> 00:35:32,516
Because of what I saw in
detention and the injustice

579
00:35:34,521 --> 00:35:37,151
And my brother had a cell phone

580
00:35:37,881 --> 00:35:40,797
I took it from him
and kept using it

581
00:35:40,822 --> 00:35:43,193
For two or three months,
then I gave it back to him

582
00:35:44,417 --> 00:35:47,803
I stayed at home all the
time until I met a friend

583
00:35:51,266 --> 00:35:55,198
This is my friend

584
00:35:56,839 --> 00:35:58,844
More than a brother

585
00:36:01,032 --> 00:36:04,495
When I started going out to the
street after that year and a half

586
00:36:04,964 --> 00:36:08,271
When I went out, I
didn’t raise my head

587
00:36:08,688 --> 00:36:10,120
I kept my head down
toward the ground

588
00:36:10,145 --> 00:36:11,084
And my hand was in my pocket

589
00:36:13,922 --> 00:36:16,579
So he began encouraging
me, walking with me

590
00:36:17,959 --> 00:36:19,912
He walked with
me wherever I went

591
00:36:22,859 --> 00:36:26,349
Many of his friends told
him—Don’t walk with him

592
00:36:26,714 --> 00:36:28,927
He’s suspicious and
will ruin your reputation

593
00:36:29,552 --> 00:36:31,323
He told them—It’s
none of your business

594
00:36:31,348 --> 00:36:34,552
This is my affair and I
want to accompany him

595
00:36:34,813 --> 00:36:37,833
And he’s still with me,
always encouraging me

596
00:36:38,745 --> 00:36:41,245
Because of him I started
taking my hand out in the street

597
00:36:41,688 --> 00:36:43,979
I walk proudly and don’t
pay attention to anyone

598
00:36:44,474 --> 00:36:46,401
And I don’t listen to
this one or that one

599
00:36:46,426 --> 00:36:48,302
And thank God
